.SH SHPowerSpectrum
Compute the power spectrum of a real function.
.SH Usage
call SHPowerSpectrum (\f[CR]cilm\f[R], \f[CR]lmax\f[R],
\f[CR]pspectrum\f[R], \f[CR]exitstatus\f[R])
.SH Parameters
.TP
\f[CR]cilm\f[R] : input, real(dp), dimension (2, \f[CR]lmaxin\f[R]+1, \f[CR]lmaxin\f[R]+1)
The function expressed in real spherical harmonics.
.TP
\f[CR]lmax\f[R] : input, integer(int32)
The maximum spherical harmonic degree used in calculating the power
spectrum.
This must be less than or equal to \f[CR]lmaxin\f[R].
.TP
\f[CR]pspectrum\f[R] : output, real(dp), dimension (\f[CR]lmax\f[R]+1)
The power spectrum of the function.
.TP
\f[CR]exitstatus\f[R] : output, optional, integer(int32)
If present, instead of executing a STOP when an error is encountered,
the variable exitstatus will be returned describing the error.
0 = No errors; 1 = Improper dimensions of input array; 2 = Improper
bounds for input variable; 3 = Error allocating memory; 4 = File IO
error.
.SH Description
\f[CR]SHPowerSpectrum\f[R] will calculate the power spectrum of a
function expressed in real 4\-pi normalized spherical harmonics.
For a given spherical harmonic degree \f[CR]l\f[R], this is calculated
explicitly as:
.PP
\f[CR]pspectrum(l) = Sum_{i=1}\(ha2 Sum_{m=0}\(hal cilm(i, l+1, m+1)**2\f[R].
